Can the euro be fixed?
Paris — Recently, German Finance Minister Wolfgang Schäuble has brought up the option of Greece leaving the euro, hoping to send a signal that no member state can be exempt from the strict discipline of the monetary union.
In fact, his proposal sparked a major debate about the principles that form the foundation of the euro, the governance model of the euro, and the rationale for the euro's existence.
Two weeks before the Schäuble proposal was put forward, European leaders had already noted a report on the future of the euro written by Jean-Claude Juncker, the President of the European Commission, and his colleagues from other EU institutions. However, the new debate over Greece led many policymakers to believe it was necessary to return to the original starting point.
At the same time, citizens are questioning why they should share a common currency?
Does this make sense? Can we reach a consensus on the future of Greece?
Currency is like a nation; it requires a myth to establish it.
Traditional wisdom holds that the euro was the political price Germany paid for reunification.
In fact, the reunification of Germany was merely the final step in an engineering effort that had already taken shape in the 1980s to resolve a long-standing problem.
European governments strongly opposed floating exchange rates, considering them incompatible with the single market; at the same time, they were unwilling to retain the German-dominated monetary system in the long term.
A genuine European currency based on German principles seems to be the best solution.
In retrospect, the reunification of Germany proved to be more of a curse than a blessing.
When exchange rates were fixed in 1999, Germany was overvalued and faced significant economic difficulties, while France was undervalued and experiencing economic prosperity.
In the following decade, the imbalance gradually emerged between the resurgent Germany and countries experiencing credit booms due to low interest rates.
And with the outbreak of the global financial crisis in 2008, these conditions became a breeding ground for a perfect storm.
No one knows what Europe would be like without the euro.
Will the fixed exchange rate system continue or collapse?
Can the German马克 be overvalued again?
Will countries reintroduce trade barriers and end the single market?
Could a real estate bubble emerge in Spain?
Will government reform result in more or less?
It is impossible to establish a baseline for reverse analysis to assess the impact of the euro.
But this is certainly not a reason for complacency.
Over the past 15 years, the performance of the Eurozone economy has been disappointing, and its political institutions must bear responsibility for this.
What truly matters is whether a common European currency will still be important in the future.
This issue is often avoided because the cost of leaving the euro is unimaginably high (and if the breakup of the eurozone were to occur during a crisis, exacerbating tensions among member states, the costs would be even higher).
In addition, abolishing the euro may unleash the dark forces of nationalism and protectionism.
However, Kevin O'Rourke from the University of Oxford recently pointed out that this view is not sufficient.
Logically, this is equivalent to suggesting that a couple should stay married simply because the cost of divorce is too high.
So, does the euro still make sense?
Originally, people expected the euro to bring three major economic benefits.
People assume that a currency union can promote economic integration and consolidate Europe's long-term growth.
On the contrary, trade and investment within the Eurozone have grown sluggishly, and the growth potential has in fact been weakened.
Partly because national governments have not taken further steps to build the Eurozone into an economic superpower on the basis of monetary union, but instead have tried to retain the remaining powers they have.
This may make political sense, but it is economically worthless: Europe's large internal market is one of its main assets, and therefore, opportunities to strengthen the internal market must never be wasted.
Secondly, people hope that the euro will become one of the major international currencies (especially considering that few countries meet the necessary legal, market, and policy institutions).
And according to the latest data from the European Central Bank, this hope has basically been realized.
The euro's international use ranks second to the dollar, a achievement that helps Europe continue to influence the global economic order rather than becoming an irrelevant entity.
Third, people (not without a touch of naivety) believe that the institutions underpinning the euro are capable of improving the overall quality of economic policy, as if the level of policy-making at the European level were inherently superior to that at the national level.
After the global financial crisis of 2008, a severe test came: the Eurozone overestimated the fiscal dimension of the crisis and underestimated its financial dimension, resulting in a performance that was worse than that of the United States and the United Kingdom.
If the euro is to bring prosperity, further reforms in policy and institutional systems must be implemented.
However, formulating and implementing a schedule requires a broad consensus on the nature of the problem.
The ongoing debates over the Greek issue indicate that Europe is still far from reaching a consensus: participating countries have conflicting analyses regarding the root causes of the debt crisis, resulting in contradictory remedies proposed.
Richard Cooper from Harvard University once observed that in the early stages of international public health cooperation, the governance of global diseases was greatly hindered by the differing patterns of infectious diseases across countries.
All countries favor joint actions, but they cannot form a unified plan because they disagree on how infectious diseases spread from one country to another.
This is the problem the Eurozone is facing today.
Fortunately, this problem is not unsolvable. Major reforms such as establishing the European Stability Mechanism and launching the banking union have proven this point.
Inconsistencies have not prevented the European Central Bank from taking decisive action, indicating that institutional governance indeed matters.
But the fact that reforms and actions have only recently begun, and were implemented under the pressure of a serious crisis, has made us clearly aware of the difficulty in reaching a consensus.
Europe can no longer delay or pretend any longer.
Member states of the Eurozone must establish a consistent agenda on governance and political reform to transform the monetary union into an engine of prosperity; otherwise, they will continue to mire themselves in repeated disputes and crises until citizens lose patience or markets lose confidence.
Clarity is a prerequisite for serious discussion and significant reform.
Nowadays, all major stakeholders have an obligation to clearly define what they consider indispensable, what they find unacceptable, and what they are willing to offer in exchange for what they desire.
